From: aorus-5090-egpu <noreply@example.invalid>
Date: Wed, 6 May 2026 15:30:00 +1000
Subject: [PATCH] Lever M-recover: diagnostic telemetry for Commit 3 design

Adds 4-point timeline instrumentation reading PMC_BOOT_0 + WPR2_ADDR_HI
at key driver lifecycle points:

  - probe-end          (nv_pci_probe, after BAR0 mapped + Commit 2 check)
  - startdev-entry     (nv_start_device, on /dev/nvidia0 open path)
  - pre-rmInit         (nv_start_device, immediately before rm_init_adapter)
  - post-rmInit-{OK,FAIL} (nv_start_device, immediately after rm_init_adapter)

All log at NV_DBG_ERRORS so visible at default verbosity. Each line:
  [DIAG]: site=<X> bar0=0x<X> PMC_BOOT_0=0x<X> WPR2_ADDR_HI=0x<X>
          WPR2_VAL=0x<X> WPR2_up=YES/no parent_bridge=<BDF>

Background: 2026-05-06 15:18 cold-cold-boot validation of Commit 2
(probe-time WPR2 detection at offset 0x88a828) showed fire_count=0
despite kernel _kgspBootGspRm correctly logging WPR2-up. Confirmed not
a code-path / dispatch / kill-switch issue. The diagnostic answers
*where* in the lifecycle WPR2 transitions to non-zero, so Commit 3 can
hook the trigger at the right point.

Decision matrix the diagnostic resolves:

  WPR2 timeline       | Commit 3 design
  --------------------|----------------------------------------
  0,0,0,nz            | Hook nv_start_device pre-rmInit (alt 2)
  0,0,0,0             | Pivot to NVOC kgspBootGspRm hook (alt 1)
  nz everywhere       | Investigate ioremap/mapping mechanism
  any 0xFFFFFFFF      | Bus dies in lifecycle; different problem

Instrumentation-only — no behaviour change. PMC_BOOT_0 reads serve as
bus-alive sanity check.

Removed once Commit 3 design finalised, OR gated behind a kill switch.

Bumps version 595.71.05-aorus.7 → aorus.8.

Tasks: #62
---
diff --git a/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.c b/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.c
index 1000ae98..9b306d76 100644
--- a/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.c
+++ b/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.c
@@ -172,6 +172,89 @@ static DEVICE_ATTR(tb_egpu_lever_m_surrenders, 0444,
 static DEVICE_ATTR(tb_egpu_lever_m_last_fire_jiffies, 0444,
                    tb_egpu_lever_m_last_fire_jiffies_show, NULL);
 
+/* Diagnostic telemetry helper (2026-05-06).
+ *
+ * Reads PMC_BOOT_0 (bus-alive sanity) and WPR2_ADDR_HI (stuck check) via
+ * temporary ioremap, logs both at NV_DBG_ERRORS along with upstream
+ * bridge BDF. Called from 4 lifecycle points to build a timeline that
+ * conclusively determines where Commit 3 should hook its trigger.
+ *
+ * After Commit 3 design is finalised, this diagnostic is removed or
+ * gated behind a kill switch. For now it's always-on — no perf concern,
+ * runs ~4 times per boot + once per persistenced retry.
+ */
+void tb_egpu_lever_m_diag_dump(nv_linux_state_t *nvl, const char *site)
+{
+    nv_state_t   *nv;
+    struct pci_dev *pdev;
+    struct pci_dev *parent;
+    void __iomem *map_pmc;
+    void __iomem *map_wpr2;
+    u64           bar0_phys;
+    u64           wpr2_page_aligned;
+    u32           wpr2_page_offset;
+    u32           pmc_boot_0 = 0xdeadbeefu;
+    u32           wpr2_raw   = 0xdeadbeefu;
+    bool          pmc_ok = false, wpr2_ok = false;
+
+    if (!nvl)
+    {
+        nv_printf(NV_DBG_ERRORS,
+            "AORUS Lever M-recover [DIAG]: site=%s nvl=NULL — cannot read\n",
+            site);
+        return;
+    }
+
+    nv   = NV_STATE_PTR(nvl);
+    pdev = nvl->pci_dev;
+    bar0_phys = nv->bars[NV_GPU_BAR_INDEX_REGS].cpu_address;
+
+    if (bar0_phys == 0)
+    {
+        NV_DEV_PRINTF(NV_DBG_ERRORS, nv,
+            "AORUS Lever M-recover [DIAG]: site=%s bar0_phys=0 — BAR not yet captured; skipping\n",
+            site);
+        return;
+    }
+
+    /* Read PMC_BOOT_0 at offset 0 — bus-alive canary. */
+    map_pmc = ioremap(bar0_phys, PAGE_SIZE);
+    if (map_pmc)
+    {
+        pmc_boot_0 = ioread32(map_pmc);
+        iounmap(map_pmc);
+        pmc_ok = true;
+    }
+
+    /* Read WPR2_ADDR_HI at offset 0x88a828. */
+    wpr2_page_aligned = (bar0_phys + TB_EGPU_LEVER_M_WPR2_REG_OFFSET) & PAGE_MASK;
+    wpr2_page_offset  = (bar0_phys + TB_EGPU_LEVER_M_WPR2_REG_OFFSET) & ~PAGE_MASK;
+    map_wpr2 = ioremap(wpr2_page_aligned, PAGE_SIZE);
+    if (map_wpr2)
+    {
+        wpr2_raw = ioread32(map_wpr2 + wpr2_page_offset);
+        iounmap(map_wpr2);
+        wpr2_ok = true;
+    }
+
+    /* Parent bridge — Commit 3's pci_reset_bus() target candidate. */
+    parent = pdev ? pci_upstream_bridge(pdev) : NULL;
+
+    NV_DEV_PRINTF(NV_DBG_ERRORS, nv,
+        "AORUS Lever M-recover [DIAG]: site=%-18s bar0=0x%llx "
+        "PMC_BOOT_0=%s%08x WPR2_ADDR_HI=%s%08x WPR2_VAL=0x%08x WPR2_up=%s "
+        "parent_bridge=%s\n",
+        site,
+        (unsigned long long)bar0_phys,
+        pmc_ok ? "0x" : "MAPFAIL:",
+        pmc_boot_0,
+        wpr2_ok ? "0x" : "MAPFAIL:",
+        wpr2_raw,
+        wpr2_raw & TB_EGPU_LEVER_M_WPR2_VAL_MASK,
+        ((wpr2_raw & TB_EGPU_LEVER_M_WPR2_VAL_MASK) != 0) ? "YES" : "no",
+        parent ? pci_name(parent) : "NULL");
+}
+
 /* Commit 2: probe-time WPR2-stuck detection.
  *
  * Reads the GSP MMU WPR2 status register via a temporary ioremap of a
diff --git a/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.h b/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.h
index cf14bab9..24111803 100644
--- a/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.h
+++ b/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.h
@@ -89,4 +89,29 @@ void tb_egpu_lever_m_recover_stop(nv_linux_state_t *nvl);
 bool tb_egpu_lever_m_check_wpr2_at_probe(nv_linux_state_t *nvl,
                                         u64 bar0_phys_addr);
 
+/* Diagnostic telemetry for Commit 3 design (2026-05-06).
+ *
+ * Reads NV_PMC_BOOT_0 (bus-alive sanity, BAR0+0) and
+ * NV_HUBMMU_PRI_MMU_WPR2_ADDR_HI (BAR0+0x88a828) at multiple driver
+ * lifecycle points; logs each at NV_DBG_ERRORS so the timeline is
+ * visible at default verbosity. Also logs upstream bridge BDF (Commit 3
+ * reset target candidate). This is instrumentation-only — no behaviour
+ * change, no recovery action.
+ *
+ * Goal: after one reboot with this diagnostic, dmesg `[DIAG]` markers
+ * conclusively answer "where in the lifecycle should Commit 3 hook the
+ * trigger?" — by showing timeline of WPR2 register state across:
+ *   - nv_pci_probe entry (post pci_enable_device)
+ *   - nv_pci_probe end (post BAR0 mapping; current Commit 2 site)
+ *   - nv_start_device entry (open path)
+ *   - nv_start_device just before rm_init_adapter
+ *
+ * Caller passes `site` as a short string label (e.g. "probe-entry").
+ * The helper handles bar0_phys_addr=0 / nvl=NULL gracefully.
+ *
+ * After Commit 3 design is finalised, this diagnostic is removed; or
+ * alternatively kept as a NVreg_TbEgpuLeverMDiagEnable opt-in.
+ */
+void tb_egpu_lever_m_diag_dump(nv_linux_state_t *nvl, const char *site);
+
 #endif /* _NV_LEVER_M_RECOVER_H_ */
diff --git a/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-pci.c b/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-pci.c
index 95ad91fd..512083f0 100644
--- a/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-pci.c
+++ b/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-pci.c
@@ -1935,6 +1935,11 @@ nv_pci_probe
     (void)tb_egpu_lever_m_check_wpr2_at_probe(nvl,
         nv->bars[NV_GPU_BAR_INDEX_REGS].cpu_address);
 
+    /* AORUS Lever M-recover diagnostic (2026-05-06): visible-at-default-
+     * verbosity probe-end snapshot of PMC_BOOT_0 + WPR2_ADDR_HI for
+     * Commit 3 design. Removed once diagnostic complete. */
+    tb_egpu_lever_m_diag_dump(nvl, "probe-end");
+
     nv->pci_info.vendor_id = pci_dev->vendor;
     nv->pci_info.device_id = pci_dev->device;
     nv->subsystem_id       = pci_dev->subsystem_device;
diff --git a/kernel-open/nvidia/nv.c b/kernel-open/nvidia/nv.c
index c27955fb..886159b2 100644
--- a/kernel-open/nvidia/nv.c
+++ b/kernel-open/nvidia/nv.c
@@ -36,6 +36,7 @@
 #include "nv-reg.h"
 #include "nv-msi.h"
 #include "nv-pci-table.h"
+#include "nv-lever-m-recover.h"  /* AORUS Lever M-recover diag (2026-05-06) */
 #include "nv-chardev-numbers.h"
 
 #if defined(NV_UVM_ENABLE)
@@ -1386,6 +1387,12 @@ int nv_start_device(nv_state_t *nv, nvidia_stack_t *sp)
     NvBool remove_numa_memory_kthread_init = NV_FALSE;
     NvBool power_ref = NV_FALSE;
 
+    /* AORUS Lever M-recover diagnostic (2026-05-06): nv_start_device
+     * entry — typically fires when /dev/nvidia0 is opened (e.g.
+     * persistenced, ollama). Captures WPR2/PMC state at the start of
+     * the open path, before any RM init has touched it this session. */
+    tb_egpu_lever_m_diag_dump(nvl, "startdev-entry");
+
     rc = nv_get_rsync_info();
     if (rc != 0)
     {
@@ -1522,14 +1529,29 @@ int nv_start_device(nv_state_t *nv, nvidia_stack_t *sp)
         }
     }
 
+    /* AORUS Lever M-recover diagnostic (2026-05-06): immediately
+     * before rm_init_adapter — this is where _kgspBootGspRm will be
+     * called and where the kernel's own kgspIsWpr2Up_HAL reads the
+     * WPR2 register. Compare this site's reading with probe-end to
+     * see if WPR2 transitions during the driver lifecycle. */
+    tb_egpu_lever_m_diag_dump(nvl, "pre-rmInit");
+
     if (!rm_init_adapter(sp, nv))
     {
+        /* AORUS Lever M-recover diagnostic: post-rmInit FAILURE path —
+         * captures WPR2/PMC state immediately after rm_init_adapter
+         * returned failure. If WPR2 transitioned from clear (pre) to
+         * non-zero (post-fail), GSP firmware is what sets the register
+         * during its boot attempt. */
+        tb_egpu_lever_m_diag_dump(nvl, "post-rmInit-FAIL");
         NV_DEV_PRINTF(NV_DBG_ERRORS, nv,
                       "rm_init_adapter failed, device minor number %d\n",
                       nvl->minor_num);
         rc = -EIO;
         goto failed_release_irq;
     }
+    /* AORUS Lever M-recover diagnostic: post-rmInit SUCCESS path. */
+    tb_egpu_lever_m_diag_dump(nvl, "post-rmInit-OK");
 
     /* Generate and cache the UUID for future callers */
     (void)rm_get_gpu_uuid_raw(sp, nv);
